title.narrative: EQUITABLE WATER ACCESS

description.narrative: By 2023 state and non-state actors have strengthened capacity to implement programmes to increase equitable access to basic, safe, climate resilient water supply for people at home, in schools, and health care facilities in targeted UNICEF districts., which contributes to Water. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Fostering Innovation And Use Of New Technologies, Harnessing Power Of Business And Markets, Operational Support To Programme Delivery, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: By 2023, underserved children equitably use safe water and practise safe sanitation and hygiene, including during humanitarian situations.

title.narrative: By 2023 state and non-state actors have strengthened capacity to implement programmes to increase equitable access to basic, safe, climate resilient water supply for people at home, in schools, and health care facilities in targeted UNICEF districts.

description.narrative: UNICEF's water supply work has also been adjusted to support COVID activities, with SOPs strengthened for reusable bottled water sellers, and reusable bottled water sales channels used for COVID-19 RCCE. Water supply service delivery capacity, including for increased climate resilience, has been strengthened, including extension of services to targeted poor households. Work is on-going to strengthen operations and maintenance systems for community PPP models for piped water supply; approaches to improved climate resilient water supply; quality assurance; and structured engagement with private bottled and piped systems operators. | Status:On-track | As-of Date:21/08/2020
